description: Four to five on the move across the trails.

Rough-skinned Newts

I fished five Rough-skinned Newts out of the motel pool yesterday. There's barely any chlorine in the pool, as its been closed for months during the winter; however, I don't want any of these little critters to drown so I relocated them all to a nearby creek.  Last fall, I was fishing them out and relocating them on an almost daily basis.

I wash my hands routinely after handling them -- and I'll be even more vigilant with washing up in the future, now that I've learned about their neurotoxin skin secretions.

description: The baby newt was found under a rock near turtle pond on a very hot/sunny day. The mud under the rock was very moist/wet. There is no canopy cover over the rock. The rock was about 3 meters from the water in turtle pond (the water in the pond had receded a great distance due to the drought). The newt was brown/grey in color. The newt is about 1.5 inches long. The newt did not like the direct sunlight. When the rock was lifted, the newt immediately moved towards the cool grass (that was located around the edges of the rock). There was another newt under the same rock and under other rocks around the dry pond.

The newt was found in a small pool about 5.5 feet in diameter and 1/2 feet deep. The pool was located in an oak forest in a dry creek bed. A small stream (an extremely small stream that was probably only a few centimeters deep), that ran across the trail and downhill towards the pool,  fed the creek. Although there were many leaves, branches, and other debris in the pool, the water was clear. When the bottom of the pool was disturbed, the water became cloudy. There were approximately 5-7 Northern Rough Skin Newts in the pool and possibly 1-2 California newts. The rough skin newt has a dark grey/brown back (that blended in very well with the bottom of the pool) and a bright orange underside. One California Rough Skin Newt was about 4/5 inches in length and another was about 8 inches in length. One newt came up for air during this observation, so the bright orange belly could be easily observed. A wasp nest was also found close by (approximately 3-5 feet downstream). There was about 75-80% canopy cover over the pool.
This newt was swimming in a large puddle in a dry creek bed. The pool was about 5.5 feet in diameter and had leaves and grass floating in it. It was about .5 feet deep. It was 4-5 inches long.

description: Darker black one to the left

Encountering all three species of newt within a meter of each other was a piece of luck! This shot shows another way to tell apart Taricha torosa and T. granulosa: in the former, the yellow coloration extends right up to the eye, and in the latter the dark coloration tends to extend below the eye. Stebbins actually says you should check the color of the lower eyelid, which seems somewhat absurd, unless it has its eye closed, like this T. granulosa does.
